name: "Chinese" Garage
description: A Grade II listed motor garage and petrol station built in the style of a Japanese pagoda in 1928. Now a Tesco Express.
address: Chinese Garage, Stone Park Avenue, BR3 3FE

name: 198 Contemporary Arts and Learning
description: 198 Contemporary Arts & Learning is a Black-led and -owned visual arts organisation. Thirty years after starting as a social space for the Black community in the 1980s, it has recently won the freehold to the site.

name: 25 Cannon Street
description: Situated adjacent to St. Paul’s Cathedral, our reworking of this six-storey neo-classical building has created 116,000 sq ft of high-quality office space, three levels of communal terraces and a large new garden designed by Tom Stuart-Smith

name: Aldgate Square
description: Publicly accessible landscaped Square featuring a pavilion with an asymmetrical steel structure and sliding glass walls set between three triangular support points. Also a stunning contemporary outdoor artwork from Sculpture in the City.

name: Altab Ali Park
description: Altab Ali Park was renamed in 1998 after a murdered 25-year-old Bangladeshi Sylheti clothing worker. Formerly known as St. Mary's Park, it is the site of the old 14 C white church, St. Mary Matfelon which gave Whitechapel its name.

name: Alton Estate
description: Alton Estate is renowned for its mix of high-rise Le Corbusian architecture in Alton West & its low-rise Scandinavian approach to modernism in Alton East. Designed by the London County Council  architects they completed in 1959.

name: Apo Kew Bridge
description: This is a community-driven development fulfilling the burgeoning demand for urban renting. With bespoke dwellings, onsite team and amenities to meet a variety of needs, it’s not just a home but a complete hub of urban activity.
address: Galleria House, 2 Lionel Road South, Brentford

name: Argentine Ambassador's Residence
description:
"ARGENTINA AT THE LONDON DESIGN FESTIVAL 2022" 
During Open House Festival people will have the unique opportunity to visit and explore the historic mansion host to the exhibition “Creative experience- From Argentina to the world”

name: Bow Street Police Museum
description: Discover the history of law and (dis)order in Covent Garden through the architecture of No. 28 Bow Street. This tour takes place outside and will focus on the external features of the former Bow Street Magistrates' Court and Police Station.

name: Burlington House: Royal Astronomical Society
description: The home of the Royal Astronomical Society since 1874, refurbished in 2007. Part of the extension to Burlington House to provide accommodation for learned societies.

name: Fitzrovia Chapel
description: Loughborough Pearson's red brick building is unimposing from the outside, but inside is a riot of Gothic Revival design. Golden mosaics reveal the character of the Grade II* listed chapel, built as part of the Middlesex Hospital.

name: Fleet Street heritage sundial
description: This new sundial faces East so gets only morning sun. It is 10 m. square and was opened in 2021, and is publicly accessible 24/7

name: Fore Street Art Trail
description: Enjoy a self guided walking tour of Fore Street to see a wide range of public art including murals and sculptures.
address: Fore Street, Angel Edmonton, Enfield, N18 2UE

name: Grand Junction at St Mary Magdalene Church, Paddington
description: Grade I Victorian Gothic church by G E Street, architect of the Royal Courts of Justice. The recent conservation project reveals the majestic colours of Daniel Bell's painted ceiling, plus Dow Jones Architects' contemporary heritage wing.
address: Rowington Close, St Mary Magdalene's Church

name: Guildhall Yard
description: Publicly accessible space outside the spectacular Grade I listed medieval civic Guildhall.

name: Hyde Park Chapel
description: The four-story Church façade and prominent seven-story tower is covered in Portland stone and highlighted by a golden steeple. The interior features the Christus statue and a large mural of the resurrected Jesus Christ.

name: Ingrebourne Valley Visitor Centre
description: Ingrebourne Valley Visitor Centre, at Hornchurch Country Park, the Former RAF Hornchurch Airfield.

name: National Youth Theatre
description: Completed in Summer 2021, the National Youth Theatre has been redeveloped to double its capacity for studio space and was designed with young people, for young people. Recipient of the Mayor of London's Good Growth Fund.

name: New London Architecture
description: Visit New London Architecture's pop-up gallery at Westfield Stratford City to see the largest model of London. Celebrate the 10-year anniversary of the Games and learn more about the past and future of Queen Elizabeth Olympic Park.
address: The Street , Westfield Stratford City , E20 1EN

name: Nunhead Cemetery
description: Magnificent Victorian cemetery with Gothic chapel & restored & ruined lodge. One of London's wildest cemeteries. Part restored with the help of a lottery grant. 52 acres of woodland, with bats, owls, foxes & squirrels. Grade II*  landscape.

name: People's Museum Somers Town
description:
A great little museum set in the Grade 2 listed Ossulston Estate - a prime example of pre-war Social housing - based on Karl Marz Hof in Vienna.
Open Wednesdays to Saturdays throughout Festival 
Sunday 11th Event

name: Public Meeting: Time for Change: A New Vision for Convoys Wharf
description: A community-run evening of talks and discussions on the future development of Convoys Wharf. The historically important 40 acre site is slated for a controversial large-scale re-development. A must for all concerned about London's future.
address: Armada Centre, Armada Court, 21 McMillan St

name: Pushkin House
description: The independent cultural centre Pushkin House will contribute to this year's Open House Festival through a programme of events and community initiatives at its Grade-II listed building in Bloomsbury Square.

name: Remembering the 2012 Olympic Opening Ceremonies exhibition launch and walk
description: Join Eastside Community Heritage (charity developing local community history & archives) in the Olympic Park for their exhibition launch and guided walk, remembering the spectacular Olympic and Paralympic Opening Ceremonies 10 years on.
address: The View Tube, Marshgate Lane, E15 2PJ

name: Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists
description: A modern conversion of a 19th-century hop warehouse and a 1980s office building, joined by a striking helical staircase. It is the home of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists and other women’s health organisations.

name: Small Beer Brewery
description: The Small Beer Brewery was founded in 2017 by James Grundy and  Felix James. It is the first of its kind, specialising in brewing world class beer at a sociable strength.

name: St Bride's Church, Fleet Street
description: Wren designed building of 1675, interior lost in blitz of 1940, reopened 1957 with 'Wren inspired' interior
address: St Bride's Church, St Bride's Avenue, EC4Y 8AU

name: St Giles’ Cripplegate
description: A rare surviving medieval church in The City of London. 2nd bomb of the Blitz hit it. Poet John Milton buried beneath the chancel step. Early Jewish graveyard. Beside the old London Wall. Shakespeare, Bunyan, Blake & Defoe all feature.

name: St. Joseph's Church & Quiet Garden
description: A lower-ground level church space, originally a school-chapel. Stained glass windows (1820's) are from the original St. Mary Moorfields Church. 2 icons in contemporary Ethiopian-style depict Mary, Mother of the City & St. Joseph.

name: Studio Wayne McGregor
description: Studio Wayne McGregor is a world-class creative arts space, containing extraordinary dance studios and a series of playful spaces in which to collaborate, make and create - part of a new technological and creative community of east London.
address: Broadcast Centre, Here East, 10 East Bay Lane

name: The Church of Our Most Holy Redeemer
description: A unique II* listed Italianate church by John Dando Sedding with attached Campanile and Institute Building. Of particular significance in the church is the imposing baldacchino over the High Altar, which dominates the east end.

name: The City Churches: St Mary-le-Bow
description: Founded by William the Conqueror's Archbishop Lanfranc in 1080 (the significant crypt survives) St Mary-le-Bow was rebuilt, notably by Wren after the Great Fire and by Laurence King in 1964 after WWII destruction. Home of Bow Bells.

name: The City Churches: St Stephen Walbrook
description: Wren's own and 'finest City Church'.  Fantastic architecture with different shapes,  twelve Corinthian columns and covered by huge dome - first of its type. Central stone altar by Henry Moore installed in 1987. Birthplace of the Samaritans.

name: The Experimental Weave Lab
description: The Experimental Weave Lab is the City of London’s first contemporary weaving studio. For Open House London we are throwing open the doors to our studio for a work in progress exhibition and live weaving.
address: St Olave Parish Hall, Mark Lane, EC3R 7LQ

name: The Family Kitchen, Royal Botanic Gardens Kew
description: The Family Kitchen & Shop, Royal Botanic Gardens Kew, designed by architects HOK with front of house interiors by Mizzi Studio and Lumsden Design, is an environmentally driven, education-led food space for visitors of all ages.
address: Royal Botanic Gardens,   , Kew Rd, TW9 3AB

name: The Foundry
description: Tucked behind a busy road in W12, this former foundry is a multi-level development featuring an architects’ studio with courtyards and spaces for exhibitions and musical performances. The  building's 15m brick chimney is a local landmark.

name: The Horseshoe Bend Kiosk, St James's Park, Near Buckingham Palace
description: Part of a public realm enhancement project across London’s Royal Parks from 2017 to 2021, architecture and design practice Mizzi Studio saw the installation of a brass tubular food kiosk in St James' Park at the foot of Buckingham Palace.
address: The Horseshoe Kiosk, St James' Park

name: The Old Town Hall, Richmond
description: Red brick and Bath stone grand 'Elizabethan Renaissance' style building altered by war, political changes and reflecting Richmond's history. Guided tours on 17 September start at the war memorial, Whittaker Avenue, on the hour 10am-2pm.
address: Old Town Hall, Whittaker Avenue, Richmond

name: The Photography Foundation Open House (D2)
description:
Come and see our light filled space, green exterior and find out more about what we do at The Photography Foundation! 

Browse our mini exhibition & zines, and have your photo taken in our pop-up studio by one of our alumni.

name: The Place
description:
Grade II listed building from 1889 with diverse historical functions - now functioning as Theatre venue and dance studios.
A more recent remodelling and additional dance studios has made the complex a bright and contemporary venue.

name: The Post Building
description:
London is known for its rooftops. The Roof Garden at The Post Building has been designed as a one-off location for enjoyment, work and wellness looking out over some of its most memorable.

Open to the public 7 days a week!

name: The Serpentine Coffee House, The Royal Parks, Opposite The Serpentine Gallery
description:
The Serpentine Coffee House overlooking the Serpentine Lake designed by Mizzi Studio, with its undulating brass canopy roof that echoes a stingray’s flight through water,  has added a
new architectural landmark to London’s Hyde Park.
address: The Serpentine Coffee House, W Carriage Drive

name: Tour through the exhibition Fantasies on a Found Phone, Dedicated to the Man Who Lost it
description: Join a tour through the exhibition Fantasies on a Found Phone, Dedicated to the Man Who Lost it by artist Mahmoud Khaled. The artist transformed The Mosaic Rooms period, domestic architecture, inspired by research on historic house museums

name: Trading Places - The changing face of the Royal Docks
description: Come and explore the history of the Royal Docks, once a global centre of maritime trade. Recognising the impact of the decline and closure of the docks, we will look to the future and the next chapter for this special part of our city.
address: Meet at the Landing Statue (outside ExCel)

name: UPDATED: City Information Centre
description: London's main tourist information centre is clad in a specially manufactured system of 220 pre-finished stainless steel panels. The subtly reflective surface provides a striking counterpoint to St Paul's. NOTE: Closed on Monday 19 September

name: UPDATED: Guildhall Art Gallery
description:
UPDATED: Open daily 10.30am-4pm. Closed Mon 19 September.
Guided tours 12.15pm & 1.15pm on Tuesdays, Thursdays, Fridays, Saturdays & Sundays, see below.
Home of the City of London's art collection, & remains of London's Roman Amphitheatre

name: UPDATED: London's Roman Amphitheatre
description:
UPDATED: Open daily 10.30am-4pm Closed Mon 19 September.
Combined guided tours of Amphitheatre and Guildhall Art Gallery at 12.15pm & 1.15pm on Tuesdays, Thursdays, Fridays, Saturdays & Sundays.
The capital’s only known Roman Amphitheatre
address: London’s Roman Amphitheatre at Guildhall Art Ga

name: UPDATED: The City Centre
description: UPDATED: Drop-in Monday - Friday only. (not open weekends). Learn about the built environment of the City of London. See the interactive 1:500 scale Pipers model of the City with the latest developments and architecture.

name: Uncommon Projects
description: Uncommon Projects moved into their new showroom in June 2022. The showroom will be open for walk in visitors for the duration of Open House.

name: Union Chapel
description: A Grade I and II*  treasure that’s home to an inclusive church, an award winning venue, a unique organ and The Margins Project for those in crisis in London. Book organ workshop and performance https://unionchapel.org.uk/venue/whats-on

name: Walworth Garden
description: Our timber frame building was designed by Matrix Feminist Design Co-Operative, and built by women. It represents our community's history of activism-the same ethos that transformed our site from dereliction, into a thriving community garden

name: Water Conduit, Richmond Park
description: A walking tour in Richmond Park to the White Conduit, which was constructed in Tudor times to carry fresh water to the now defunct Richmond Palace. This listed structure is not usually open to the public.

name: Westminster station tours
description: This short tour will take you through Westminster station, a brutalist dream and one of the most beloved stations on the Underground network. We will discuss the station's architecture and how it has been modified since reopening in 1999.

name: Witches & Witchcraft History Tour
description: For thousands of years witches of all form have walked the isles of Britain and been the topic of folklore and history. On this tour led by Vincent Edward Manda from Wonders of London we discover more about the witches of London.
address: outside the exit just by Trinity Square Gardens

name: Woolwich Town Hall
description: Florid Edwardian Baroque. Domed entrance hall, grand staircase and stained glass windows, a great example of civic architecture of the time belonging to the Classical tradition rather than the Gothic Revival favoured outside London.

name: Woolwich Works
description: Carved out of five historic military Grade II and II* listed buildings, Woolwich Works is a new cultural destination in London located in the royal Arsenal.

name: Yorkton Workshops
description: Yorkton Workshops was restored from a series of dilapidated Victorian stables into a new permanent studio, archive and workshop for Pearson Lloyd. The space also provides a gallery, event space and location available for hire.
